threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects a suspicious ELF binary with UPX compression
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a MIPS ELF binary, identified as a variant of the Mozi botnet. It exhibits multiple malicious behaviors, including propagation via exploits (TR-064, HNAP, CVE-2017-17215), downloading and executing further payloads (e.g., '/Mozi.a;sh${IFS}/tmp/Mozi.a&'), and achieving persistence by modifying startup scripts (`/etc/rc.d/rc.local`, `/etc/init.d/S95baby.sh`) and remounting filesystems as read-write. It also manipulates `iptables` to ensure its P2P C2 communication is not blocked. The presence of numerous strings like 'Mozi.m', 'Mozi.a', and command injection patterns confirm its malicious nature.
